# Lived body, not furniture — simplify and expand

When writing fatigue, stress, or domestic cost in Solmare chapters:

## Prefer the person

Do **not** personify chairs, cushions, rooms, or slate stacks as the ones who “remember” or “forgive.”

| Weak | Prefer |
|------|--------|
| The chair had not forgiven him. The cushion remembered wrong angles. | His body had not forgiven him for it. His neck was stiff. |
| The room remembered every argument. | The slate stack was taller than when he had last looked — unfinished briefs, unanswered notes. |

**Test:** Is the object feeling, or is the person? Keep the person.

## Simplify and expand

When a fatigue / cost beat is thin or cute, **simplify the metaphor and expand the concrete**:

- One clear physical fact (stiff neck, knot in shoulder, unread message)
- One clear situational fact (slate pile, meetings that did not stop)
- Ordinary corridor / room texture only as backdrop

Do **not** stack clever furniture captions. Do **not** leave the beat as a single wink.

## Do not recycle Book One domestic check-ins

Especially kill as habit:

- *Are you eating*
- Food / sleep nag messages as the default spouse / family beat
- The same three-word domestic ping used for every exhausted officer

If a partner / family message is needed, make it **specific to this chapter** (e.g. *when are you coming home*) — or show the unread queue without quoting a spent Book One line.

